Self-Harness (Minimal) — Build Spec

A small, runnable proof-of-concept of the Self-Harness loop (arXiv:2606.09498): an LLM agent that improves its own operating harness — not its weights — by mining its failures, proposing small edits to its prompt/scaffold, and keeping only edits that pass regression tests.

This spec is written to be handed to Claude Code. Build it incrementally in the order given. Keep it minimal — the goal is to watch the harness improve over a few rounds, not to reproduce the paper's benchmark numbers.


1. Core idea (so you have context while building)


Model M is fixed. We never train or fine-tune. It is called via API.
Harness h is everything around the model: the system prompt, instructions, output-format rules, a checklist, retry logic. This is the only thing that changes.
The same model M plays two roles: it solves tasks (the agent), and it proposes fixes to its own harness (the improver).
Improvement is an iterative loop over T rounds. Each round turns failure evidence into candidate harness edits, validates them, and merges the survivors.


The whole loop is Algorithm 1 in the paper. Implement it literally.


2. Scope & non-goals

In scope


One fixed model via the Anthropic API.
A small verifiable task suite (auto-graded, no human in the loop).
The three stages: Weakness Mining → Harness Proposal → Proposal Validation.
Held-in / held-out split with a strict acceptance rule.
Full logging of every round, edit, and score.


Out of scope (do NOT build)


No fine-tuning / weight updates.
No Docker, no Terminal-Bench, no multi-model comparison.
No web UI. CLI + log files only.



3. Task suite (the keystone)

The loop only works if outcomes are automatically verifiable. Default to unit-tested coding tasks because they're fully self-contained (no DB, no external services).

Provide ~20 small "write a Python function" tasks, each as:

tasks/
  task_001/
    prompt.md        # natural-language problem statement
    tests.py         # asserts that import and check `solution`
  task_002/
    ...

A task passes iff the model's returned code defines the required function and all asserts in tests.py pass when run in a sandboxed subprocess (timeout + restricted namespace).


Alternative suite (optional flag --suite sql): Text-to-SQL over a bundled SQLite DB, graded by comparing returned rows to a gold result set. Use this if you'd rather reuse an existing LLM-as-judge evaluator. Default remains coding.



Split: deterministically partition tasks into held_in (mine failures from these) and held_out (never tuned on; used only to catch overfit edits). Default 60/40, seeded.


4. Harness representation

Represent the harness as a dict of named, editable text blocks so edits stay small and mergeable:

pythonharness = {
  "role": "You are a careful Python programmer.",
  "strategy": "",          # starts empty — room to grow
  "output_format": "Return ONLY a fenced ```python code block.",
  "checklist": "",         # starts empty
}

The system prompt sent to M is just these blocks concatenated in a fixed order. Starting harness h0 should be deliberately minimal so there's headroom to improve.

An edit is a structured op on one block:

python{"op": "append" | "replace", "block": "checklist", "text": "...", "rationale": "..."}

Constrain proposals to be minimal and targeted: one block, tied to one named failure pattern. Reject edits that try to rewrite everything.


5. Components to implement

5.1 model.py — fixed model wrapper


Single function call_model(system: str, user: str) -> str.
Uses the Anthropic API. Read ANTHROPIC_API_KEY from env.
Default model: a cheap one (Haiku-class) — the loop is call-heavy (K candidates × tasks × 2 splits × T rounds).
Add basic retry/backoff and a hard token cap.


5.2 evaluate.py — EVALUATE(M, h, split)


Runs M under harness h on every task in a split.
Returns (pass_rate, records) where records is a list of per-task {task_id, passed, model_output, error, trace}.
Sandbox test execution (subprocess, timeout ~10s, no network).


5.3 mine.py — Weakness Mining


Input: the failed records from the held-in run.
Ask M to cluster the failures into a few (≤5) named, model-specific failure patterns (e.g. "off-by-one on ranges", "forgets edge case: empty input", "wraps code in prose"), each with 1–2 example task ids.
Output a compact evidence bundle B_t (JSON).


5.4 propose.py — Harness Proposal


Input: current harness h_t + evidence bundle B_t.
Ask M to produce K diverse but minimal candidate edits, each tied to exactly one failure pattern. (K default 4.)
Return list of structured edit ops (Section 4).


5.5 validate.py — Proposal Validation (the strict gate)

For each candidate edit e:


Apply e to h_t → h_candidate.
EVALUATE on both held-in and held-out.
Δ_in  = pass_rate_in(h_candidate)  − pass_rate_in(h_t)
Δ_out = pass_rate_out(h_candidate) − pass_rate_out(h_t)
Accept iff Δ_in ≥ 0 and Δ_out ≥ 0 and max(Δ_in, Δ_out) > 0.
(No regression on either split; strict improvement on at least one.)
Accepted → keep (edit, Δ_in, Δ_out). Else → reject (log the reason).


5.6 merge.py — MERGEACCEPTED(h_t, accepted)


If nothing accepted → h_{t+1} = h_t (unchanged).
Else → apply all accepted edits to produce h_{t+1}.
Handle two edits touching the same block deterministically (e.g. order by Δ, append in sequence).


5.7 loop.py — main driver (Algorithm 1)

load tasks, split held_in / held_out
h = h0
for t in range(T):
    pass_in, records_in = EVALUATE(M, h, held_in)
    pass_out, _         = EVALUATE(M, h, held_out)
    log_round_start(t, pass_in, pass_out, h)

    B = mine(failed(records_in))
    candidates = propose(M, h, B, K)

    accepted = []
    for e in candidates:
        h_c = apply(e, h)
        d_in  = EVALUATE(M, h_c, held_in).pass_rate  - pass_in
        d_out = EVALUATE(M, h_c, held_out).pass_rate - pass_out
        if d_in >= 0 and d_out >= 0 and max(d_in, d_out) > 0:
            accepted.append((e, d_in, d_out)); log_accept(e, d_in, d_out)
        else:
            log_reject(e, d_in, d_out)

    h = h if not accepted else merge(h, accepted)
    snapshot_harness(t, h)
return h


